Nov 14 2009 	Good proximity to old Dubai but watch the cigarette smoke	In case people are confused, the Ascot Hotel and Royal Ascot Hotel and right next to each other and share some common facilities (e.g. basement parking, swimming pool, fitness center). I stayed at the Ascot Hotel, the Royal Ascot is more expensive and I don't know what you got for the extra money.It was close to old Dubai, you had to cross Khalid Bin Waleed street and you were there. There's a free breakfast buffet and it's extensive - all the way from fresh fruit and smoked salmon to sausage, made to order omelettes and even an Indian curry.The free parking is appreciated since it's difficult to find parking in that part of town. If you're willing to go the public route instead, there are bus stops right outside the hotel and you're about 1km from the Metro Stop (subway). There will be a stop that's even closer but it's currently under construction.The rooms were fine. There was about a 30 inch flat screen tv and plenty of tv channels with programming in English, Arabic, Hindi, French, etc. There's an in-room safe but because there's a shelf, I couldn't fit my 15&quot; laptop diagonally. But I didn't notice anything missing.I ate at the Thai restaurant and I thought the food was pretty good. I had a pad thai type dish and a salad.I had two gripes - paid wifi access and cigarette smoke. The hotel charges 60 dirhams a day for WiFi access. The speeds are pretty good but there are others in the vicinity that offer it for free.I thought the cigarette smoke was the bigger issue. There's a bar (Waxy O'Connors) on the premises and one entrance to the bar is through a corridor in the hotel room area on the 1st floor (2nd floor if you're American). I think the smoke must come from there. The smoke seeps in every where and I think they use air freshener to cover the smell. That's the only reason I don't recommend this hotel. There are several hotels about a block from this hotel - Dor El Sandos, Ramee, etc.	
